This is almost always caused by one of three things:

**1. Parent passes a new object/array/function reference every render**
```jsx
// BAD — new object created every render, triggers child re-render
<Child style={{ color: 'red' }} />
<Child items={data.filter(d => d.active)} />
<Child onClick={() => setOpen(true)} />

// GOOD — stable references
const style = useMemo(() => ({ color: 'red' }), []);
const activeItems = useMemo(() => data.filter(d => d.active), [data]);
const handleClick = useCallback(() => setOpen(true), []);
```
Objects, arrays, and functions are compared by REFERENCE, not by value. `{} !== {}` even if they look identical. Every render creates new references.

**2. Component isn't wrapped in React.memo**
By default, React re-renders a child whenever the parent re-renders, even if props are identical. Wrap the child:
```jsx
const Child = React.memo(function Child({ name, onClick }) {
  return <button onClick={onClick}>{name}</button>;
});
```
Now it only re-renders when `name` or `onClick` actually change (by reference).

**3. Context provider value changes**
If your component consumes a context, and the provider value changes, ALL consumers re-render:
```jsx
// BAD — new object every render
<Ctx.Provider value={{ user, theme }}>

// GOOD — memoize the value
const value = useMemo(() => ({ user, theme }), [user, theme]);
<Ctx.Provider value={value}>
```

**How to diagnose:** Add `console.log('Child rendered')` at the top of the component. Then use React DevTools Profiler → check "Record why each component rendered" to see exactly which prop changed.

