The script is running before the DOM element exists. Your JS loads and tries to find the element, but the HTML hasn't been parsed yet.

**Fix 1: Move `<script>` to end of `<body>`**
```html
<!-- BAD — script in <head> runs before body exists -->
<head><script src="app.js"></script></head>

<!-- GOOD — script at end, all elements exist -->
<body>
  <button id="btn">Click</button>
  <script src="app.js"></script>
</body>
```

**Fix 2: Use DOMContentLoaded**
```javascript
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
  const btn = document.getElementById('btn');
  btn.addEventListener('click', handleClick);
});
```

**Fix 3: Check before using**
```javascript
const btn = document.getElementById('btn');
if (btn) {
  btn.addEventListener('click', handleClick);
} else {
  console.error('Button #btn not found in DOM');
}
```

Most likely cause: your `<script>` tag is in `<head>` or above the element it references. Move it to the end of `<body>`. Share your HTML and I'll confirm.

This is a stale closure or stale cache issue. The data was fetched once, cached, and isn't refetched when you navigate back.

**If using useEffect for fetching:**
```jsx
// This only runs once if deps don't change
useEffect(() => {
  fetchData();
}, []); // ← empty deps = mount only

// Fix: add a dependency that changes on navigation
const { id } = useParams();
useEffect(() => {
  fetchData(id);
}, [id]); // ← refetches when route param changes
```

**If using React Query / SWR:**
The data is cached. Options:
```javascript
// React Query — set staleTime to 0 so it always refetches
const { data } = useQuery(['user', id], fetchUser, { staleTime: 0 });

// Or invalidate on navigation
queryClient.invalidateQueries(['user']);
```

**If using client-side state (useState):**
State persists if the component doesn't unmount. React Router keeps mounted components alive by default.
```jsx
// Force reset on route change
useEffect(() => {
  setData(null); // Clear old data
  fetchData();   // Fetch fresh
}, [location.pathname]);
```

**If using Next.js App Router:**
Server components refetch automatically. If you're in a client component, the issue is the same as above — useEffect doesn't re-run unless deps change.

The root cause is almost always: the fetch runs on mount, the component doesn't unmount on navigation, so the fetch never re-runs. Add the route param or pathname to the dependency array.

This means you're trying to call something that isn't a function. Three common causes:

**1. Wrong import — importing a value instead of a function:**
```javascript
// The module exports an object, not a function
import config from './config';
config(); // TypeError: config is not a function
// config is { apiUrl: '...', timeout: 5000 }

// Fix: use the value, don't call it
console.log(config.apiUrl);
```

**2. Shadowed variable name:**
```javascript
const data = await fetch(url); // data is a Response object
const data = await data.json(); // WRONG — you just reassigned 'data'
data(); // TypeError

// Fix: use different variable names
const response = await fetch(url);
const data = await response.json();
```

**3. Method doesn't exist on the type you think:**
```javascript
const result = document.getElementById('btn');
result.map(r => ...); // TypeError: result.map is not a function
// getElementById returns ONE element (or null), not an array

// Fix: use querySelectorAll for multiple
const results = document.querySelectorAll('.btn');
Array.from(results).map(r => ...); // NodeList → Array first
```

Check the line number in the error, look at what you're calling `()` on, and verify its actual type with `console.log(typeof x)` right before the call.

The form is doing a traditional HTML submit (full page reload) instead of being handled by JavaScript.

**Fix: Prevent the default form submission:**
```javascript
// Vanilla JS
form.addEventListener('submit', (e) => {
  e.preventDefault(); // ← This is the key line
  // Now handle it with JS
  const formData = new FormData(form);
  // ... send via fetch
});
```

```jsx
// React
const handleSubmit = (e) => {
  e.preventDefault(); // ← Must be first line
  // ... handle submission
};
return <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>...</form>;
```

**Alternative: Make the button not a submit button:**
```html
<!-- This submits the form: -->
<button type="submit">Send</button>

<!-- This doesn't: -->
<button type="button" onclick="handleSubmit()">Send</button>
```

**Common mistake in React:** Using `onClick` on a button inside a `<form>` without `type="button"`. Buttons default to `type="submit"` inside forms.

```jsx
// BAD — this submits the form AND calls onClick
<form>
  <button onClick={handleClick}>Save</button>
</form>

// GOOD — either prevent default or use type="button"
<form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>
  <button type="submit">Save</button>
</form>
```

The text is wider than the screen. Common causes and fixes:

**1. Long URLs or strings without spaces:**
```css
.text {
  overflow-wrap: break-word;  /* breaks long words */
  word-break: break-word;     /* fallback for older browsers */
}
```

**2. Fixed width container on small screens:**
```css
/* BAD */
.container { width: 800px; }

/* GOOD */
.container { width: min(100% - 48px, 800px); margin: 0 auto; }
```

**3. Font size too large for mobile:**
```css
/* Use clamp for fluid typography */
h1 { font-size: clamp(1.8rem, 5vw, 3.5rem); }
```

**4. Flexbox child not shrinking:**
```css
/* Flex items won't shrink below their content by default */
.flex-child {
  min-width: 0;  /* Allow shrinking below content size */
  overflow: hidden;
  text-overflow: ellipsis;
  white-space: nowrap;
}
```

**5. Pre-formatted or code text:**
```css
pre, code {
  white-space: pre-wrap; /* Wrap instead of horizontal scroll */
  max-width: 100%;
  overflow-x: auto;     /* Or allow horizontal scroll */
}
```

**6. Global prevention — add to your reset:**
```css
html { overflow-x: hidden; }
*, *::before, *::after { box-sizing: border-box; }
img, video, iframe { max-width: 100%; height: auto; }
```

The nuclear option `overflow-x: hidden` on html hides the symptom. Find and fix the actual element that's overflowing — use DevTools → toggle device toolbar → look for horizontal scroll.

This is expected in React 18 Strict Mode. It's not a bug — it's a feature.

In development, React intentionally mounts → unmounts → remounts every component to help you find missing cleanup functions. Your effect runs on mount, cleanup runs on unmount, effect runs again on remount = 2 calls.

**This does NOT happen in production.** Only in development with StrictMode enabled.

**You should NOT remove StrictMode to fix this.** Instead, make your effects work correctly when run twice:

```jsx
// BAD — doesn't handle double-mount
useEffect(() => {
  fetchData().then(setData);
}, []);

// GOOD — cleanup cancels the first fetch
useEffect(() => {
  const controller = new AbortController();

  fetch('/api/data', { signal: controller.signal })
    .then(r => r.json())
    .then(setData)
    .catch(e => {
      if (e.name !== 'AbortError') console.error(e);
    });

  return () => controller.abort(); // cleanup
}, []);
```

**The same applies to subscriptions and timers:**
```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  const id = setInterval(tick, 1000);
  return () => clearInterval(id); // cleanup prevents double interval
}, []);
```

If your effect does something that can't be undone (like sending an analytics event), use a ref to track if it already ran:
```jsx
const sent = useRef(false);
useEffect(() => {
  if (sent.current) return;
  sent.current = true;
  sendAnalytics();
}, []);
```

But the real lesson: if double-mounting breaks something, your effect is missing a cleanup function. Fix the cleanup, don't suppress the double-mount.

Safari has several rendering differences from Chrome. Here are the most common issues and fixes:

**1. Flexbox gap not supported (Safari < 14.1):**
```css
/* Use margin instead of gap for older Safari */
.flex-container { display: flex; gap: 16px; }
/* Fallback: */
.flex-container > * + * { margin-left: 16px; }
```

**2. backdrop-filter needs -webkit prefix:**
```css
.glass {
  -webkit-backdrop-filter: blur(20px);
  backdrop-filter: blur(20px);
}
```

**3. 100vh is taller than visible area on iOS Safari:**
```css
/* BAD — includes the URL bar height on iOS */
.hero { height: 100vh; }

/* GOOD — uses dynamic viewport height */
.hero { height: 100dvh; }
/* Or fallback: */
.hero { height: 100vh; height: 100dvh; }
```

**4. Smooth scrolling not supported by default:**
```css
/* Chrome: works. Safari: might not */
html { scroll-behavior: smooth; }
/* Fallback: use JS scrollIntoView({ behavior: 'smooth' }) */
```

**5. Date input rendering differs:**
Safari renders `<input type="date">` differently. Use a date picker library for consistent cross-browser UI.

**6. Font rendering:**
Safari uses different font smoothing. Add:
```css
body {
  -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased;
  -moz-osx-font-smoothing: grayscale;
}
```

Test in Safari's DevTools (Develop menu) or use BrowserStack for cross-browser testing.

The warning 'Can't perform a React state update on an unmounted component' means you're calling setState after the component has already unmounted — usually from an async operation that completes after navigation.

**Fix 1: AbortController for fetch (recommended):**
```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  const controller = new AbortController();

  fetch('/api/data', { signal: controller.signal })
    .then(r => r.json())
    .then(data => setData(data))
    .catch(e => {
      if (e.name !== 'AbortError') throw e;
    });

  return () => controller.abort();
}, []);
```

**Fix 2: Cleanup flag for non-fetch async:**
```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  let cancelled = false;

  someAsyncOperation().then(result => {
    if (!cancelled) setData(result);
  });

  return () => { cancelled = true; };
}, []);
```

**Fix 3: Clear timers:**
```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  const timer = setTimeout(() => setVisible(true), 2000);
  return () => clearTimeout(timer);
}, []);
```

**Fix 4: Unsubscribe from subscriptions:**
```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  const unsubscribe = eventEmitter.on('update', setData);
  return () => unsubscribe();
}, []);
```

The pattern is always the same: return a cleanup function from useEffect that cancels whatever async operation is in progress. If every async operation has a cleanup, you'll never see this warning.

Two approaches — CSS-only for simple cases, JS for dynamic style changes:

**CSS-only (just sticky, no style change):**
```css
header {
  position: sticky;
  top: 0;
  z-index: 100;
  background: rgba(14, 14, 20, 0.85);
  backdrop-filter: blur(16px);
  border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.06);
}
```

**JS + CSS (changes style on scroll):**
```javascript
const header = document.querySelector('header');

window.addEventListener('scroll', () => {
  header.classList.toggle('scrolled', window.scrollY > 50);
}, { passive: true }); // passive = better scroll performance
```

```css
header {
  position: fixed;
  top: 0;
  left: 0;
  right: 0;
  z-index: 100;
  padding: 24px 32px;
  background: transparent;
  transition: all 0.3s ease;
}

header.scrolled {
  padding: 12px 32px;
  background: rgba(14, 14, 20, 0.95);
  backdrop-filter: blur(20px);
  border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.06);
  box-shadow: 0 4px 20px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3);
}
```

Key details: Use `position: fixed` (not sticky) when you want to transform the header. Add `{ passive: true }` to the scroll listener for performance. Transition only the properties that change. Add padding-top to the body equal to the header height so content isn't hidden underneath.

For luxury, you want fonts that feel refined, exclusive, and timeless.

**Display/headings:** Cormorant Garamond (300-400 weight, light and elegant) or Playfair Display (for more dramatic contrast). Both have beautiful thin strokes that signal high-end.

**Body:** Nunito Sans (300-400 weight, clean, airy) or DM Sans (400, geometric but warm).

**Why these work:** Luxury is about restraint and space. Light font weights + generous letter-spacing + ample whitespace = expensive feeling. Heavy fonts feel industrial, not refined.

**CSS:**
```css
--font-display: 'Cormorant Garamond', serif;
--font-body: 'Nunito Sans', sans-serif;

