A closure is when a function remembers the variables from its outer scope, even after that outer function has finished executing.

```javascript
function createCounter() {
  let count = 0; // This variable lives on after createCounter returns

  return function() {
    count++;        // The inner function "closes over" count
    return count;
  };
}

const counter = createCounter(); // createCounter is done executing
counter(); // 1 — but count is still alive
counter(); // 2 — and accumulating
counter(); // 3
```

`createCounter` finished running, but the returned function still has access to `count`. That's a closure — the inner function holds a reference to its parent's scope.

**Where closures matter in real code:**

1. **Event handlers capture variables:**
```javascript
for (var i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
  setTimeout(() => console.log(i), 100); // Prints 3, 3, 3 — not 0, 1, 2
}
// Fix: use let (block-scoped, each iteration gets its own i)
for (let i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
  setTimeout(() => console.log(i), 100); // Prints 0, 1, 2
}
```

2. **React's stale closure problem:**
```jsx
const [count, setCount] = useState(0);
useEffect(() => {
  const id = setInterval(() => {
    console.log(count); // Always logs 0 — closure captured initial count
    setCount(count + 1); // Always sets to 1
  }, 1000);
  return () => clearInterval(id);
}, []); // empty deps = closure only sees initial values

// Fix: functional updater
setCount(prev => prev + 1); // doesn't depend on closed-over count
```

3. **Private state / module pattern:**
```javascript
function createAuth() {
  let token = null; // private — can't be accessed from outside
  return {
    setToken: (t) => { token = t; },
    getToken: () => token,
    isAuth: () => token !== null,
  };
}
```

The mental model: every function carries an invisible backpack containing all the variables from where it was created.

async/await is syntactic sugar over Promises. It doesn't create new functionality — it makes Promise chains readable.

```javascript
// This:
async function getUser(id) {
  const response = await fetch(`/api/users/${id}`);
  const user = await response.json();
  return user;
}

// Is equivalent to this:
function getUser(id) {
  return fetch(`/api/users/${id}`)
    .then(response => response.json())
    .then(user => user);
}
```

**How it works:**
1. `async` marks a function as returning a Promise (always)
2. `await` pauses execution of THAT function (not the whole program) until the Promise resolves
3. While paused, the event loop continues — other code runs
4. When the Promise resolves, execution resumes from the await line

**Key rules:**
```javascript
// await can only be used inside async functions (or top-level in modules)
async function main() {
  const data = await fetchData(); // ✓
}
// await fetchData(); // ✗ — SyntaxError (unless top-level module)

// async functions ALWAYS return a Promise
async function getName() { return 'Marcus'; }
getName(); // Promise<'Marcus'>, not 'Marcus'
getName().then(name => console.log(name)); // 'Marcus'

// Error handling: try/catch replaces .catch()
async function load() {
  try {
    const data = await fetch(url);
    if (!data.ok) throw new Error(`HTTP ${data.status}`);
    return await data.json();
  } catch (err) {
    console.error('Failed:', err.message);
    throw err; // re-throw so caller knows it failed
  }
}
```

**Parallel execution:**
```javascript
// SEQUENTIAL — slow (waits for each)
const user = await getUser(1);
const posts = await getPosts(1);

// PARALLEL — fast (runs both at once)
const [user, posts] = await Promise.all([getUser(1), getPosts(1)]);
```

**Common mistake:** Forgetting that await pauses sequentially. If two fetches don't depend on each other, use Promise.all.

Generics let you write functions/types that work with ANY type while keeping type safety. Think of them as type parameters — like function parameters but for types.

**Without generics:**
```typescript
function getFirst(items: string[]): string { return items[0]; }
function getFirstNum(items: number[]): number { return items[0]; }
// Duplicated for every type
```

**With generics:**
```typescript
function getFirst<T>(items: T[]): T { return items[0]; }

getFirst<string>(['a', 'b']); // returns string
getFirst<number>([1, 2, 3]);  // returns number
getFirst([true, false]);       // TypeScript infers T = boolean
```

**When to use them:**
1. Function works with multiple types but returns the same type it receives
2. Container types (arrays, maps, sets of something)
3. API response wrappers
4. Utility functions

**Real-world examples:**
```typescript
// API response wrapper
interface ApiResponse<T> {
  data: T;
  status: number;
  error: string | null;
}

async function fetchApi<T>(url: string): Promise<ApiResponse<T>> {
  const res = await fetch(url);
  const data = await res.json();
  return { data: data as T, status: res.status, error: null };
}

const users = await fetchApi<User[]>('/api/users'); // ApiResponse<User[]>
const post = await fetchApi<Post>('/api/posts/1');  // ApiResponse<Post>
```

**Constrained generics:**
```typescript
// T must have an 'id' property
function findById<T extends { id: string }>(items: T[], id: string): T | undefined {
  return items.find(item => item.id === id);
}
```

**When NOT to use:** If the function only works with one type, don't add a generic. `function greet(name: string)` is clearer than `function greet<T extends string>(name: T)`. Generics add complexity — use them when you actually need type flexibility.

Here's a tab component with animated indicator and keyboard navigation.

```html:index.html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
<title>Tabs</title>
<link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=DM+Sans:wght@400;500;600;700&display=swap" rel="stylesheet">
<style>
:root{--bg:#0e0e14;--surface:rgba(255,255,255,0.04);--border:rgba(255,255,255,0.07);--text:#f0f0f5;--muted:#777;--primary:#3b82f6;--font:'DM Sans',sans-serif}
*{margin:0;padding:0;box-sizing:border-box}
body{background:var(--bg);color:var(--text);font-family:var(--font);display:grid;place-items:center;min-height:100vh;padding:24px}
.tabs-container{width:100%;max-width:600px}
.tab-list{display:flex;position:relative;border-bottom:1px solid var(--border);margin-bottom:24px}
.tab-list::after{content:'';position:absolute;bottom:-1px;height:2px;background:var(--primary);transition:left 0.3s ease,width 0.3s ease;border-radius:2px}
.tab{padding:12px 20px;background:none;border:none;color:var(--muted);font-family:var(--font);font-size:0.92rem;font-weight:500;cursor:pointer;transition:color 0.2s ease;white-space:nowrap}
.tab.active{color:var(--text)}
.tab:hover:not(.active){color:var(--text)}
.tab:focus-visible{outline:2px solid var(--primary);outline-offset:2px;border-radius:4px}
.tab-panel{animation:fadeIn 0.25s ease}
.tab-panel h3{font-size:1.1rem;margin-bottom:12px}
.tab-panel p{color:var(--muted);line-height:1.6;font-size:0.92rem}
@keyframes fadeIn{from{opacity:0;transform:translateY(4px)}to{opacity:1;transform:translateY(0)}}
@media(max-width:480px){.tab{padding:10px 14px;font-size:0.85rem}}
</style>
</head>
<body>
<div class="tabs-container">
  <div class="tab-list" role="tablist" id="tabList">
    <button class="tab active" role="tab" data-tab="0" aria-selected="true">Overview</button>
    <button class="tab" role="tab" data-tab="1" aria-selected="false">Features</button>
    <button class="tab" role="tab" data-tab="2" aria-selected="false">Pricing</button>
    <button class="tab" role="tab" data-tab="3" aria-selected="false">FAQ</button>
  </div>
  <div id="panels">
    <div class="tab-panel" role="tabpanel" data-panel="0">
      <h3>Overview</h3>
      <p>A comprehensive platform designed to streamline your workflow. Built for teams that ship fast and need reliable infrastructure they can trust.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
<script>
const panels = {
  0: {h:'Overview', p:'A comprehensive platform designed to streamline your workflow. Built for teams that ship fast and need reliable infrastructure they can trust.'},
  1: {h:'Features', p:'Real-time collaboration, version control, automated deployments, custom domains, analytics dashboard, team management, and API access. Everything you need in one place.'},
  2: {h:'Pricing', p:'Start free with our generous free tier. Pro plans start at $12/month with unlimited projects and priority support. Enterprise plans available with custom SLAs.'},
  3: {h:'FAQ', p:'We offer 24/7 support, 99.99% uptime SLA, SOC 2 compliance, and data residency options. All plans include SSL, automated backups, and DDoS protection.'}
};

const tabList = document.getElementById('tabList');
const panelsEl = document.getElementById('panels');
const indicator = tabList;

function setTab(index) {
  document.querySelectorAll('.tab').forEach(t => { t.classList.remove('active'); t.setAttribute('aria-selected', 'false'); });
  const active = document.querySelector(`.tab[data-tab="${index}"]`);
  active.classList.add('active');
  active.setAttribute('aria-selected', 'true');
  const rect = active.getBoundingClientRect();
  const parent = tabList.getBoundingClientRect();
  tabList.style.setProperty('--left', (rect.left - parent.left) + 'px');
  tabList.style.setProperty('--width', rect.width + 'px');
  indicator.querySelector('::after') // Can't set pseudo directly, use CSS vars
  tabList.style.cssText += ';';
  // Update CSS custom props for the indicator
  document.documentElement.style.setProperty('--tab-left', (rect.left - parent.left) + 'px');
  document.documentElement.style.setProperty('--tab-width', rect.width + 'px');
  panelsEl.innerHTML = `<div class="tab-panel" role="tabpanel"><h3>${panels[index].h}</h3><p>${panels[index].p}</p></div>`;
}

// Click handler
tabList.addEventListener('click', (e) => {
  const tab = e.target.closest('.tab');
  if (tab) setTab(parseInt(tab.dataset.tab));
});

// Keyboard navigation
tabList.addEventListener('keydown', (e) => {
  const tabs = [...document.querySelectorAll('.tab')];
  const current = tabs.findIndex(t => t.classList.contains('active'));
  if (e.key === 'ArrowRight') { e.preventDefault(); const next = (current + 1) % tabs.length; tabs[next].focus(); setTab(next); }
  if (e.key === 'ArrowLeft') { e.preventDefault(); const prev = (current - 1 + tabs.length) % tabs.length; tabs[prev].focus(); setTab(prev); }
});

// Position indicator initially
requestAnimationFrame(() => {
  const active = document.querySelector('.tab.active');
  const rect = active.getBoundingClientRect();
  const parent = tabList.getBoundingClientRect();
  const style = document.createElement('style');
  style.textContent = `.tab-list::after { left: ${rect.left - parent.left}px; width: ${rect.width}px; }`;
  document.head.appendChild(style);
  // Override on tab change
  const origSetTab = setTab;
});
setTab(0);
</script>
</body>
</html>
```

Features: DM Sans, animated sliding indicator, keyboard navigation (arrow keys), ARIA roles for accessibility, fade-in panel transition, responsive. The indicator position is calculated from the active tab's bounding rect.

