.btn:disabled { opacity:0.5; cursor:not-allowed; }
```
Usage: `<button class="btn btn-primary">Save</button>`. One base, many variants.

```javascript
// Before: createElement + appendChild
data.forEach(item => {
  const li = document.createElement('li');
  li.textContent = item.name;
  list.appendChild(li);
});

// After: template literal
list.innerHTML = data.map(item =>
  `<li>${escapeHtml(item.name)}</li>`
).join('');
```
Single DOM write (innerHTML) instead of N appendChilds. Always escape user data to prevent XSS.

Use event delegation — one listener on parent:
```javascript
container.addEventListener('click', e => {
  const btn = e.target.closest('[data-action]');
  if (!btn) return;
  const action = btn.dataset.action;
  handlers[action]?.(btn);
});
```
One listener instead of N. Works for dynamically added elements. Use data-* attributes as source of truth.

```javascript
// Before:
fetch(url).then(r => r.json()).then(data => {
  return process(data);
}).then(result => {
  display(result);
}).catch(err => handle(err));

// After:
try {
  const r = await fetch(url);
  const data = await r.json();
  const result = await process(data);
  display(result);
} catch (err) {
  handle(err);
}
```
Each `.then` becomes a line. `.catch` becomes try/catch. Same behavior, much more readable.

```javascript
// Before:
if (password.length < 8) { ... }
setTimeout(retry, 3000);
if (items.length > 50) paginate();

// After:
const MIN_PASSWORD_LENGTH = 8;
const RETRY_DELAY_MS = 3000;
const PAGINATION_THRESHOLD = 50;

if (password.length < MIN_PASSWORD_LENGTH) { ... }
setTimeout(retry, RETRY_DELAY_MS);
if (items.length > PAGINATION_THRESHOLD) paginate();
```
Names explain WHY the number exists. Makes future changes safer — update one constant, not hunt for every '8'.

JS is single-threaded but non-blocking. The event loop: call stack runs sync code → Web APIs handle async (setTimeout, fetch) → completed callbacks go to queue → event loop moves queue items to stack when stack is empty.

```javascript
console.log('1'); setTimeout(()=>console.log('2'), 0); console.log('3');
// Output: 1, 3, 2 — setTimeout goes to queue, waits for stack to clear
```
Microtasks (Promises) have higher priority than macrotasks (setTimeout).

Syntactic sugar over Promises. `async` makes a function return a Promise. `await` pauses THAT function (not the whole program) until the Promise resolves.
```javascript
async function load() {
  const res = await fetch(url); // pauses here, event loop continues
  const data = await res.json();
  return data; // returned as Promise
}
```
Parallel: `const [a,b] = await Promise.all([fetchA(), fetchB()]);`
Error handling: try/catch replaces .catch().

Runs code AFTER render for side effects (fetch, subscriptions, DOM mutations).
```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  // runs after render
  return () => { /* cleanup: cancel, unsubscribe, clear */ };
}, [deps]); // re-runs when deps change
```
Deps: `[x]` = run when x changes. `[]` = mount only. No array = every render (usually wrong).
Gotcha: missing deps = stale values. Object deps = runs every render (reference equality).

Three dots `...` that expand iterables:
```javascript
// Copy array/object (shallow)
const copy = [...arr];
const copy = { ...obj };

// Merge
const merged = { ...defaults, ...overrides };
const combined = [...arr1, ...arr2];

// Rest parameters (collecting)
function sum(...nums) { return nums.reduce((a,b) => a+b, 0); }

// Destructuring rest
const { id, ...rest } = user; // rest = everything except id
const [first, ...others] = items;
```
Spread = expanding into individual elements. Rest = collecting individual elements into one.

