Increasing hero padding from 160px to 200px top, bumping heading to clamp(40px, 7vw, 72px), and adding more bottom margin on the subtitle.

Use these CSS changes:
```css
.hero { padding: 200px 24px 100px; }
.hero h1 { font-size: clamp(40px, 7vw, 72px); }
.hero p { margin-bottom: 48px; }
```

Swapping to a violet palette. Here are the CSS variable updates:
```css
:root {
  --bg: #0d0a0f; --surface: #16111a; --surface-hover: #1e1625;
  --primary: #8b5cf6; --primary-hover: #a78bfa;
  --primary-subtle: rgba(139,92,246,0.1); --primary-glow: rgba(139,92,246,0.3);
}
```
The background gets a slight purple tint (`#0d0a0f` instead of neutral `#0a0a0f`) so the violet accent feels cohesive with the dark theme.

Adding mobile breakpoints. Key changes:

```css
@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .nav-links { display: none; }
  .hero { padding-top: 100px; text-align: center; }
  .hero h1 { font-size: 32px; }
  .hero p { font-size: 16px; }
  .features-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
  .pricing-grid { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
  .stats { gap: 24px; }
  .stat-number { font-size: 32px; }
  footer { flex-direction: column; gap: 8px; text-align: center; }
}
```

This hides nav links (you'd add a hamburger menu for production), stacks all grids to single column, reduces heading sizes, and centers the footer.

Bumping mobile font sizes for better readability:

```css
@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .hero h1 { font-size: 32px; line-height: 1.15; }
  .hero p { font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.6; }
  .feature-card h3 { font-size: 17px; }
  .feature-card p { font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.6; }
  .price-amount { font-size: 36px; }
  .section-header h2 { font-size: 28px; }
  .section-header p { font-size: 15px; }
}
```

The rule: body text never below 14px on mobile, headings never below 24px. Line heights increase slightly on mobile (1.5→1.6) because narrower columns need more breathing room.

